{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b7aa3c5f-62ee-4401-940e-514e125c219a","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_0195C9zMkhq4tjNT6Gk1UrMC","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Researching .NET 10 changes"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"6423aec5-7c45-4b1a-a99f-b03039835133","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about breaking changes and new behaviors when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each point:\n\n1. **[InlineArray] with explicit [StructLayout]** - In .NET 10, there's a breaking change where `InlineArray` types can no longer have explicit `StructLayout` attributes with `Size` specified. The runtime now calculates the size automatically.\n\n2. **DriveInfo.DriveFormat on Linux** - In .NET 10, `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux returns the file system type name instead of the mount point or other info. The actual values returned changed.\n\n\n3. **NU1510 warnings about pruned references** - .NET 10 introduces package reference pruning by default, which can produce NU1510 warnings when transitive dependencies are pruned.\n\n4. **NuGet vulnerability auditing of transitive dependencies** - .NET 10 changes the default `NuGetAuditMode` to audit transitive dependencies as well (not just direct ones).\n\n5. **FilePatternMatch.Stem null check** - In .NET 10, `FilePatternMatch.Stem` changed from `string?` to `string` (non-nullable), so null checks may produce warnings or behave differently.\n\nNow I'll walk through the practical solutions for each of these issues.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"B417:18B306:BA0BF5:E618E1:6A012DD8"},"id":"ef85958f-664a-4e2c-8d68-f80ebb9d2d1d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:16:17.878Z","parentId":"361a8510-47fe-45c0-8a25-6f495612a672"}
